==English==

===Etymology 1===
The letter name is from {{inh|en|enm|a|ā}}, from {{der|en|fro|-}}, ultimately from {{der|en|la|ā}}. Use of the Latin letter in (Old) English displaced the [[futhorc]] letter {{m|ang|ᚪ}} beginning in the 7th century, and partially also {{m|ang|ᚫ}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{q|letter name}}
** {{IPA|en|/eɪ/|a=UK,US}}
*** {{audio|en|en-us-a.ogg|a=US}}
** {{IPA|en|/æɪ/|a=AusE}}
** {{IPA|en|[eː]|a=CA}}
** {{rhymes|en|eɪ|s=1}}
*: The current pronunciation resulted from the [[w:Great Vowel Shift|Great Vowel Shift]]. Before the early part of the 17th century, the pronunciation was similar to that in other languages.
* {{q|phoneme}} {{IPA|en|/æ/|/ɑː/|/eɪ/|/ə/}}, etc.

====Letter====
{{head|en|letter|lowercase||uppercase|A|plural|as|or|a's}}

# {{Latn-def|en|letter|1}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:John Wesley Young|author2=Frank Millett Morgan|title=Elementary Mathematical Analysis|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=w:The Macmillan Company|year=1917|page=487|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/elementarymathem00younrich/page/487/mode/1up|passage=This expression is zero, for we have replaced the column of '''''a''{{'}}s''' by the column of ''b''{{'}}s and hence the determinant has two columns identical.}}
