#* {{quote-book|en|author=Margaret McPhee|title=Mistress to the Marquis|location=Toronto, Ont.|publisher=w:Harlequin Historical|year=2013|page=249|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/mistresstomarqui0000mcph/page/249/mode/1up|isbn=9781460315699|passage=Across every sheet of paper were lines and lines of letters of the alphabet. A row of '''a's''' followed by a row of b's and so on, pages of them, like pages from a copy book, crudely formed as if from the hand of a young child.}}
#* {{RQ:NYT|author=w:Rivka Galchen|title=What's Become of the So-Called Literary Bad Boy?|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219053900id_/http://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/23/books/review/whats-become-of-the-so-called-literary-bad-boy.html|date=23 February 2014|passage=In the seventh grade I admired a charismatic, witty girl who had a particular way of writing her lowercase '''a's'''. After some practice, I took to writing my lowercase '''a's''' in the same fashion.}}

=====Usage notes=====
* In English, the letter ''a'' usually denotes the [[w:near-open front unrounded vowel|near-open front unrounded vowel]] ({{IPA|en|/æ/}}), as in ''[[pad]]'', the [[w:open back unrounded vowel|open back unrounded vowel]] ({{IPA|en|/ɑː/}}) as in ''[[father]]'', the [[w:mid-central vowel|mid-central vowel]] ({{IPA|en|/ə/}}) when unstressed as in ''[[about]]'', or, when followed by another vowel, the diphthong {{IPA|en|/eɪ/}}, as in ''[[ace]]''.
* ''A'' is the third most common letter in English.

=====Derived terms=====
* Digraph sequences: [[ae]], [[ah]], [[ai]], [[au]], [[aw]], [[ay]], [[ea]], [[eau]], [[ia]], [[oa]], [[ua]]

