===Etymology 5===
From {{inh|en|enm|a}}, a reduced form of {{m|enm|he||he}}/{{m|enm|ha||he}}, {{m|enm|heo||she}}/{{m|enm|ha||she}}, {{m|enm|ha||it}}, and {{m|enm|hie|hie, hie|they}}.

====Alternative forms====
* {{l|en|'a}}

====Pronunciation====
* {{IPA|en|/ʌ/|a=RP}}
* {{sense|it}} {{IPA|en|/ʌ/|/ɑ/|a=RP}}
* {{rhymes|en|ʌ|ɑ|s=1}}

====Pronoun====
{{head|en|pronouns}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete|outside|England|and|Scotland|_|dialects}} [[he|He]], [[she]], [[they]]: the [[third-person]] [[singular]] or plural [[nominative]].<ref name=OED/>
#* '''1855''', Kingsley, ''W. Ho!'', page 120 (edition of 1889):
#*: He've a got a great venture on hand, but what '''a''' [it] be he tell'th no man.
#* '''1864''', Tennyson, ''N. Farmer, Old Style'', st. 2:
#*: Doctors, they knaws nowt, fur '''a''' [they] says what's nawways true.
## {{lb|en|obsolete|outside|England|and|Scotland|_|dialects}} [[he|He]], the [[third-person]] [[singular]] [[nominative]].
##* {{RQ:Shakespeare Much Ado About Nothing|III|ii|passage='''a’''' brushes his hat o’ mornings.}}
##* {{quote-book|en|year=1795|author=Peter Pindar|title=The Royal Visit to Exeter, a Political Epistle: by John Ploughshare ... published by Peter Pindar, Esq|page=5|text=Well! in a come [in he came]—KING GEORGE to town, / With doust and zweat az netmeg brown, / The hosses all in smoke;}}
##* '''1860''', Kite, ''Sng. Sol.'', ii, 16:
##*: A do veed amang th' lilies.
##* '''1864''', Tennyson, ''N. Farmer, Old Style'', st. 7, version of '''1917''', Raymond Macdonald Alden, ''Alfred Tennyson, how to Know Him'', page 226:
##*: "The amoighty's a taakin' o' you to 'issén, my friend," '''a''' said, {{...}}
##* {{RQ:Eddison Worm|page=8|passage=And, by your leave, for all the marvellous rich and sumptuous coat '''a''' weareth, he is very like a false jewel in a rich casing.}}
## {{lb|en|obsolete|outside|England|and|Scotland|_|dialects}} [[she|She]], the [[third-person]] [[singular]] [[nominative]].
##* '''1790''', Grose, ''MS. add.'' (M.):
##*: '''A''' wanted me to go with her.
##* '''1876''', Bound, ''Prov.'':
##*: Did '''a''' do it!
##* '''1883''', Hardy, ''Tover'', page 124 (edition of 1895):
##*: '''A's''' getting wambling on her pins [shaky on her legs].

