==Latgalian==

===Etymology===
Ultimately from {{der|ltg|ine-bsl-pro|*ō}}. The source is not clear:
* Probably borrowed from a {{ncog|sla}} language (compare {{ncog|ru|а}} and {{ncog|be|а}}).
* Alternatively, irregularly shortened from {{m|ltg|*''ā''}}, inherited from {{m|ine-bsl-pro||*ō}}.
Compare {{ncog|lt|o}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{ltg-IPA}}
* {{hyph|ltg|a}}

===Conjunction===
{{head|ltg|conjunctions|g=f}}

# [[and]], [[but]]

===References===
* {{R:ltg:Andronov:2008}}

==Latin==

===Etymology 1===
From {{der|la|grc|-}} {{m|grc|Α||alpha}}, likely through Etruscan.

====Pronunciation====
{{sense|letter name}}
* {{q|[[w:Classical Latin|Classical]]}} {{IPA|la|/aː/|[äː]}}
* {{q|[[w:Ecclesiastical Latin|Ecclesiastical]]}} {{IPA|la|/a/|[äː]}} <!--* {{la-IPA|ā}}-->

====Letter====
{{head|la|letter|lower case||upper case|A}}

# {{lb|la|sometimes with ''[[littera]]''}} the first letter of the Latin alphabet.
#: {{ux|la|littera '''a'''|t=the letter a|inline=1}}

===Etymology 2===
From {{der|la|ett|-}}.

====Pronunciation====
* {{q|[[w:Classical Latin|Classical]]}} {{IPA|la|/aː/|[äː]}}
* {{q|[[w:Ecclesiastical Latin|Ecclesiastical]]}} {{IPA|la|/a/|[äː]}} <!--* {{la-IPA|ā}}-->

====Noun====
{{head|la|noun|head=ā|g=f|[[Appendix:Glossary#indeclinable|indeclinable]]||cat2=indeclinable nouns}} {{cln|la|feminine indeclinable nouns}} <!--{{la-noun|ā|g=f|indecl=y}}-->

# {{n-g|The name of the letter ''{{l|la|A}}''.}}

=====Coordinate terms=====
{{list:Latin script letter names/la/simple}}
<!--

====References====
* Arthur E. Gordon, ''The Letter Names of the Latin Alphabet'' ([[w:University of California Press|University of California Press]], 1973; volume 9 of ''University of California Publications: Classical Studies''), part III: “Summary of the Ancient Evidence”, page 32<br/> Clearly there is no question or doubt about the names of the vowels A, E, I, O, U. They are simply long A, long E, etc. (ā, ē, ī, ō, ū). Nor is there any uncertainty with respect to the six mutes B, C, D, G, P, T. Their names are bē, cē, dē, gē, pē, tē (each with a long E). Or about H, K, and Q: they are hā, kā, kū — each, again, with a long vowel sound. -->

===Etymology 3===
Alternative form of {{m|la|ab}} by [[apocope]] {{q|not used before a vowel or h}}.

====Alternative forms====
* {{l|la|à}} {{q|earlier in New Latin}}
* {{l|la|ab}}

====Pronunciation====
* {{q|[[w:Classical Latin|Classical]]}} {{IPA|la|/aː/|[äː]}}
* {{q|[[w:Ecclesiastical Latin|Ecclesiastical]]}} {{IPA|la|/a/|[äː]}} <!--* {{la-IPA|ā}}-->

====Preposition====
{{la-prep|ā|ablative}}

# {{q|indicating ablation}} [[from]], [[away]] from, [[out]] [[of]]
#* {{Q|la|Julius Caesar|Bello Gallico|1|1|quote=Gallōs ab Aquītānīs Garumna flūmen, '''ā''' Belgīs Matrona et Sēquana dīvidit.|trans=The river Garonne separates the Gauls from the Aquitani; the Marne and the Seine (separate them) '''from''' the Belgae.}}
# {{q|indicating ablation}} [[down]] from
# {{q|indicating [[agency]]: source of action or event}} [[by]], [[by means of]]
#* {{Q|la|Cicero|De finibus bonorum et malorum|1|2|quote=Quamquam philosophiae quidem vituperātōribus satis respōnsum est eō librō, quō '''ā''' nōbīs philosophia dēfēnsa et collaudāta est, cum esset accūsāta et vituperāta ab Hortēnsiō.|trans=Although indeed to the vituperators of philosophy an adequate response is in that book, in which philosophy has been defended and highly praised '''by''' us [me], when it had been accused and vituperated by Hortensius.}}
# {{q|indicating [[instrumentality]]: source of action or event}} [[by]], [[by means of]], [[with]]
# {{q|indicating [[association]]}} [[to]], [[with]]
#* {{Q|la|Terence|Heauton Timorumenos|1|77|quote=Homō sum, hūmānī nihil '''ā''' mē aliēnum putō.|trans=I am a man; I consider nothing that is human alien '''to''' me.}}
# {{q|indicating [[location]]}} [[at]], [[on]], [[in]]
# {{q|time}} [[after]], [[since]]

=====Usage notes=====
Used in conjunction with passive verbs to mark the agent.
* {{ux|la|Liber '''ā''' discipulō aperītur.|The book is opened '''by''' the student.}}

