{{head|pt|pronouns|g=f|third-person singular}}

# {{senseid|pt|fsg direct objective pronoun}} [[her]], [[it]] (as a direct object; as an indirect object, see [[lhe]]; after prepositions, see [[ela]])
#: {{ux|pt|Encontrei-'''a''' na rua.|t=I met her/it on the street.|inline=1}}

=====Usage notes=====
* Becomes {{m|pt|la|-la}} after verb forms ending in ''-r, -s'', or ''-z'', the pronouns {{m|pt|nos||us}} and {{m|pt|vos||plural you}}, and the adverb {{m|pt|eis||here is; behold}}; the final letter causing the change disappears.
*: After {{m|pt|ver||to see}}: ''Posso vê-'''la'''?'' — “May I see '''her/it'''?”
*: After {{m|pt|pôs||he/she/it put}}: ''Ele pô-'''la''' ali.'' — “He put '''her/it''' there.”
*: After {{m|pt|fiz||I made; I did}}: ''Fi-'''la''' ficar contente.'' — “I made '''her/it''' become happy.”
*: After {{m|pt|nos||us}}: ''Ela deu-no-'''la''' relutantemente.'' — “She gave '''her/it''' to us reluctantly.”
*: After {{m|pt|eis||here is; behold}}: ''Ei-'''la'''!'' — “Behold '''her/it'''!”
* Becomes {{m|pt|na|-na}} after a nasal vowel or diphthong: ''-ão, -am'' [ɐ̃w̃], ''-õe'' [õj̃], ''-em, -êm'' [ẽj̃].
*: ''Detêm-'''na''' como prisioneira.'' — “They detain '''her/it''' as a prisoner.”
* In informal Brazilian Portuguese, the nominative form {{m|pt|ela||she}} is more commonly used.
*: ''Eu '''a''' vi.'' → ''Eu vi '''ela'''.'': “I saw '''her/it'''.”

=====Quotations=====
{{see citations|pt}}

=====See also=====
